{{Refimprove|date=March 2010}} {{Infobox album | name = Alice Cooper Goes to Hell | type = [[Album]] | artist = [[Alice Cooper]] | cover = Alice Cooper - Goes To Hell.jpg | alt = | released = June 25, 1976 | recorded = | venue = | studio = Soundstage, Toronto; Record Plant East, New York and RCA Recording Studios, Los Angeles | genre = [[Rock music|Rock]], [[hard rock]], [[pop rock]] | length = 43:15 | label = [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]] | producer = [[Bob Ezrin]] | prev_title = [[Welcome to My Nightmare]] | prev_year = 1975 | next_title = [[Lace and Whiskey]] | next_year = 1977 }}
{{Album ratings | rev1 = [[Allmusic]] | rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}} <ref>{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r4548|pure_url=yes}}</ref> | rev2 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' | rev2Score = mixed <ref>[https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/alice-cooper-goes-to-hell-19760826 ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110627102827/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/alice-cooper-goes-to-hell-19760826 |date=June 27, 2011 }}</ref> }}
'''''Alice Cooper Goes to Hell''''' is the ninth studio [[album]] by [[Alice Cooper]], released in 1976. A continuation of ''[[Welcome to My Nightmare]]'' as it continues the story of [[Steven (Alice Cooper character) |Steven]], this concept album was written almost exclusively by Cooper with guitar player [[Dick Wagner]] and producer [[Bob Ezrin]].<ref>{{cite AV media notes |title = Alice Cooper Goes to Hell |titlelink = Alice Cooper Goes to Hell |others = Alice Cooper |year = 1976 |pages = 12 |type = CD Booklet |publisher = [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]] Inc. |id= 2896-2 |location = 3300 Warner Blvd., [[Burbank, California]] }}</ref>
With the success of “[[Only Women Bleed]]” from his first solo effort, Alice continued with the rock ballads on this album. “[[I Never Cry]]” was written about his drinking problem, which would in one year send the performer into rehab and affect all his subsequent music up to and including 1983’s ''[[DaDa]]''.<ref>[http://www.phoenixnewtimes.com/1996-06-20/music/hangin-with-mr-cooper/2/ ‘Hanging with Mr. Cooper’]; ''[[Phoenix New Times]]'', June 20, 1996</ref> Cooper called the song “an alcoholic confession”.
The “Alice Cooper Goes To Hell” tour of 1976 was completely cancelled prior to commencement due to Cooper suffering from [[anemia]] at the time. However, “Go to Hell” proved the last song until his big hit “[[Poison (Alice Cooper song)|Poison]]” to become a consistent part of Cooper’s live setlists, being performed on most tours to the present.<ref>[http://www.setlist.fm/stats/songs/alice-cooper-63d63aa3.html?song=Go+to+Hell&artist=63d63aa3 ‘Go to Hell’ live performance data]</ref> “I Never Cry” was also regularly performed in the late 1970s and during the 2000s, whilst “Guilty” was performed regularly on the ''Flush the Fashion'' and ''Special Forces'' tours and occasionally during the 2000s<ref>[http://www.setlist.fm/stats/songs/alice-cooper-63d63aa3.html?song=Guilty ‘Guilty’ liver performance data]</ref> and “Wish You Were Here” frequently played on the tours for the following two albums.<ref>[http://www.setlist.fm/stats/songs/alice-cooper-63d63aa3.html?song=Wish+You+Were+Here ‘Wish You Were Here’ live performance data]</ref>
In 2005 the first track, “Go to Hell”, was featured as the theme song to the sixth episode of ''[[Lucy, the Daughter of the Devil]]'' titled "Human Sacrifice". The song was also featured in the 2009 video game ''[[Grand Theft Auto IV: The Lost and Damned]]'', the 1986 movie ''The American Way'', and the second season ''[[Ash vs Evil Dead]]'' episode "Last Call".
