{{Infobox Venue | name = Bowery Poetry Club | image = [[File:BoweryPoetryClub.JPG|350px|]] | image_caption = The front facade of the Bowery Poetry Club | nickname = BPC | location = [[Manhattan]], [[New York City|New York]] | type = [[Performance Art]]s venue | genre = [[Poetry]], [[Spoken Word]], [[Slam Poetry]], [[Hip-Hop]], [[Experimental theatre|Experimental Theatre]], [[Performance Art]], [[Alternative Stand Up]], [[Burlesque]], [[Live Music]] | broke_ground = | built = | opened = 2002 | renovated = | expanded = | closed = | demolished = | owner = [[Bob Holman]] | former_names = | seating_type = | seating_capacity = | website = {{URL|bowerypoetry.com}} }}
The '''Bowery Poetry Club''' is a [[New York City]] poetry performance space founded by [[Bob Holman]] in 2002. <ref name="wiyf1">Aptowicz, Cristin O'Keefe. (2008). ''Words in Your Face: A Guided Tour Through Twenty Years of the New York City Poetry Slam.'' Chapter 26: What the Heck is Going on Here; The Bowery Poetry Club Opens (Kinda) for Business. Soft Skull Press, 288. {{ISBN|1-933368-82-9}}.</ref> Located at 308 Bowery, between Bleecker and Houston Streets in [[Manhattan]]'s [[East Village, Manhattan|East Village]], the BPC is a popular meeting place for poets and aspiring artists.
==Building history== The building was built in the 1850s as a lumber yard. Its last incarnation before becoming the BPC was as a [[Formica (plastic)|formica]] tabletop manufacturer that ran on [[DC current]]. [[Plywood]] scraps were used to heat the building in a [[pot-belly stove]].
In a 2002 ''[[New York Times]]'' article about the club, Holman talked about the then-risky choice to open the club on Bowery, which at the time was a "skid row":
{{quote|text=The Bowery is a vein of change. Being blind is not the way to retain the aspects of the past that need to be honored. In order to change the world, you have to be in the world. As you get older, the risk of selling out and becoming part of that system stays real but it's mitigated by wanting to get in there and dig... I can't tell if we are making it in the big sense, but we're making an impression.<ref name="nytimes11122002">{{cite news | last = Richardson | first = Lynda | title = A Poet (and Proprietor) Is a Beacon in the Bowery | work = New York Times | date = 2002-11-12 | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2002/11/12/nyregion/public-lives-a-poet-and-proprietor-is-a-beacon-in-the-bowery.html | accessdate = 2009-09-05}}</ref>}}
The Bowery Poetry Club closed for renovations on July 17, 2012<ref>Solomon, Serena. [http://www.dnainfo.com/new-york/20120717/east-village/bowery-poetry-club-close-as-questions-linger-about-conversion-plan "Bowery Poetry Club to Close as Questions Linger About Conversion Plan"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140228230400/http://www.dnainfo.com/new-york/20120717/east-village/bowery-poetry-club-close-as-questions-linger-about-conversion-plan |date=2014-02-28 }} ''DNAinfo'' (July 17, 2012)</ref> and re-opened in March 2013 as a joint performance venue with Duane Park, which relocated from [[TriBeCa]]. In the process, BPC dropped "Club" from its name, becoming "Bowery Poetry". The venue presents Duane Park's [[burlesque]] performances Tuesdays through Saturdays, with Bowery Poetry presenting shows on Saturday afternoons, Sundays, and Mondays.<ref>Sherer, Jenna. [http://www.timeout.com/newyork/things-to-do/meet-the-new-duane-park-and-bowery-poetry "Meet the new Duane Park and Bowery Poetry"] ''[[Time Out New York]]'' (March 12, 2013)</ref><ref>Solomon, Serena. [http://www.dnainfo.com/new-york/20130130/east-village/revamped-bowery-poetry-open-march-with-new-name-new-look "Revamped Bowery Poetry to Open in March With New Name, New Look"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140228232918/http://www.dnainfo.com/new-york/20130130/east-village/revamped-bowery-poetry-open-march-with-new-name-new-look |date=2014-02-28 }} ''DNAinfo'' (January 30,20130</ref>
Bowery Poetry is operated by '''Bowery Arts + Science''', a non-profit organization founded by Bob Holman, and run by filmmaker and poet Nikhil Melnechuk.
